BLUETONGUE - EUROPE (05): SPAIN (BALEARIC ISLANDS) CATTLE, SHEEP, BLUETONGUE VIRUS SEROTYPE 4, CONTROL
******************************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Fri 2 Jul 2021
Source: Animal Health, Spain [in Spanish, machine trans., edited]
https://www.animalshealth.es/rumiantes/virus-lengua-azul-baleares-distinto-circula-espana


The Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food (MAPA) has published its report on the detection of serotype 4 of the bluetongue virus in the Balearic Islands.

The MAPA points out that the preliminary molecular studies carried out in the Central Veterinary Laboratory (LCV) of Algete on the virus indicate that the strain causing these outbreaks is similar to the one that affected the region in recent years, from the Balkans and Italy.

The report remarks that it is "therefore different from the virus present in the south of the Iberian Peninsula. In addition, in all cases, the affected animals are native to the Balearic Islands, and there have been no recent entries of animals in the farms affected," he adds.

In this way, they consider that the most likely hypothesis is the introduction of the virus by means of _Culicoides_ midges infected with the virus from other areas of the Mediterranean, as already happened in the previous outbreaks detected during the 1st decade of this century.

Likewise, the MAPA analyzes in the report the information regarding the detection of the bluetongue virus in the Balearic Islands. "The official veterinary services of the Government of the Balearic Islands have detected the circulation of serotype 4 of the Bluetongue virus in a sentinel bovine in a farm located in the municipality of Pollenca (Mallorca)," explains the ministry.

In this way, it points out that the sentinel farm, with a census of 4 bovines and 19 sheep, participates in the National Bluetongue Surveillance Program implemented in Spain.

The Balearic archipelago is located in an area so far free of the disease but considered a risk area within the framework of said program, so that it is undergoing reinforced surveillance against the disease.

Additionally, 9 clinical suspicions have been reported in sheep in farms located in the same municipality of Pollenca, and in those of Campanet and Inca, whose animals have also been positive for the bluetongue virus by serology, as well as by PCR, the latter having been also confirmed by the LCV of Algete, the national reference laboratory for the disease in Spain.

The last bluetongue outbreak in the Balearic Islands was reported in November 2003, on the island of Menorca. The Balearic Islands obtained the recognition of free against the disease after 2 years without outbreaks following the last declaration.

Given the verification of the circulation of the virus, the veterinary authorities have proceeded to establish a restriction zone around the outbreak that includes all the islands of the Balearic archipelago (Mallorca, Menorca, Ibiza, and Formentera), where prevention measures are being reinforced [by] surveillance and control in the area.

In addition, mandatory vaccination against bluetongue virus serotype 4 will be instituted for all sheep and bovine animals older than 3 months of age, and restrictions have been established on the movement of animals of species sensitive to the disease; passive surveillance has been reinforced, recalling the obligation to report any suspicion, as well as the disinsection of farms.

This new restriction zone around the outbreaks will be published in the coming days by means of a resolution.

"It is recalled that blue tongue is a viral disease that is transmitted by [midges] of the genus _Culicoides_, and that affects ruminants of different species, but in no case affects man," they conclude from the MAPA.

